Thank you for sharing your HTML and CSS code. I can see you're working on creating a website layout. As a beginner, it's great that you're experimenting with different CSS properties. Here are some suggestions to improve and simplify your layout:

1. Consistency in container widths:
   Use a consistent width for your main container. You're using 1280px in some places and 1114px in others. Stick to one width, like 1200px, for better consistency.

```css
.container {
    max-width: 1200px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 0 20px;
}
```

2. Simplify your reset CSS:
   Your reset.css is good, but you can simplify it further:

```css
* {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
}

ul, li {
    list-style: none;
}

a {
    text-decoration: none;
    color: inherit;
}
```

3. Use flexbox for layout:
   Instead of absolute positioning, use flexbox for better responsiveness. For example, for your header:

```css
.menuWrap {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    padding: 10px 0;
}

.menuWrap .gnb ul {
    display: flex;
}

.menuWrap .gnb li {
    margin-right: 20px;
}
```

4. Simplify your card layouts:
   Instead of repeating similar styles, create a reusable card class:

```css
.card {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 384px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}

.card .imgWrap img {
    width: 100%;
    transition: 0.3s;
}

.card:hover .imgWrap img {
    transform: translateY(-15px);
    box-shadow: 0 20px 40px 0 rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25);
}
```

5. Use CSS variables for colors:
   Define colors as CSS variables for easy maintenance:

```css
:root {
    --primary-color: #ffd44a;
    --text-color: #1e1e1e;
    --bg-gray: #ddd;
}
```

Then use them like this:

```css
.container .tit:after {
    background-color: var(--primary-color);
}
```

6. Improve responsiveness:
   Add media queries to make your layout responsive:

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
    .container {
        padding: 0 10px;
    }

    .menuWrap {
        flex-direction: column;
    }

    .banner ul {
        flex-direction: column;
    }
}
```

These changes will help simplify your code and make it more maintainable. Remember, CSS is about practice and iteration. Keep experimenting and learning!

